It has been more than 100 days since the presidential elections in #BelarusÂ ended.Â ForÂ more than 100 days, courageous citizensÂ haveÂ protested againstÂ the resultsÂ of the manipulated elections and the politics of autocratic president #Lukashenko.Â #100daysofviolence (1/8)

Every Sunday for the past 15 weeks, tens of thousands of them take to the streets in mass protests for justice, human rights and freedom.Â And against massive state violence: police and military have been deploying teargas and flash grenades, as well as using live bullets. (2/8)

Thousands are being detained week after week, because they refuse to accept election meddling andÂ de factoÂ dictatorship. Every week,Â there are new reportsÂ aboutÂ police violence and torture, inside the jails and outside. (3/8)

At least six people have paid for their democratic protest with their lives: Aljaksandr Tarajkouski, Aljaksandr Wichor, Henads Schutau, Gennadij Schutow, Nikita Kriwtsow and most recently Raman Bandarenka. (4/8)

They died because an autocratic regime clings to power and tries to protect its power and interests at all costs, although it has long lost public support. It is devastating to see how peaceful protests for freedom, democracy and human rights are violently broken up.Â (5/8)

The good news is: Thus far, theseÂ attemptsÂ havenâ€™t been successful.Â The protest movementâ€™s resilience and strength are admirable. But after more than 100 days, public attention has shifted away from the conflict in #Belarus.Â (6/8)

Therefore, it is now more important than ever to bring it back to internationalÂ attention toÂ reaffirm strongly: Germany and the #EU stand by the protesters.Â We stand for freedom and democracy. We condemn police brutality and state violence against peaceful protesters. (7/8)

End the violence. Respect the protest. Political process involving opposition and civil society must start now, working towards constitutional reform and peaceful transformation. Stop trying to silence the voice of the people! #westandbyyou(8/8)
